def propublica_data(url):
    return requests.get(url, headers={"X-API-Key": "api-key-here"}).json()

def paginated_request(url, num_results):
    """
    Given a url ending with 'offset=', creates a dataframe with the specified number of results (in multiples of 20)
    """    
    dfs = []
    for i in range(0, num_results, 20):
        data = propublica_data(url + str(i))
        df = pd.DataFrame(data["results"][0])
        dfs.append(df)
    return pd.concat(dfs)

def remove_spines(ax, sides=["top", "right"]):
    """
    Removes spines from all graphs in given axis. Works with an individual axis or list of axes.
    By default removes top and right spines. Returns ax.
    """
    for side in sides:
        try:
            for a in ax:
                a.spines[side].set_visible(False)
        except:
            ax.spines[side].set_visible(False)
    return ax

def date_range(df):
    """
    Returns series with pandas datetime range of [first_col, second_col] for each row
    """    
    start = df.iloc[0]
    end = df.iloc[1]       
    if pd.isna(start):
        start = end
    # means recession is ongoing
    if pd.isna(end):
        end = date.today()
    return pd.date_range(start, end)
recession_range = recession_dates.apply(date_range, axis=1)
congress_range = all_congress_dates.apply(date_range, axis=1)

# if there is a recession at any time--even a day--in the congressional session, the new df will be True at that session
def in_recession(df, min_days=1):
    """
    Given a df with a date range in each row, 
    finds when those ranges interlap--by default, even by one day--with recessions.
    Returns dataframe with same indices as df and boolean values corresponding to the existence of an interlap.
    """
    for rr in recession_range.values:
        if df.isin(rr).sum() >= min_days:
            return True
    return False

congress_recessions = congress_range.transform(in_recession, min_days=1)
congress_recessions = congress_recessions.to_frame("Recession")

def statements_paginated(statement_url, num_results, start=0, type_="statement"):
    """
    Takes a url corresponding to statements (w/o pagination) and returns a dataframe with the given number of results.
    Sometimes, the offset will not be valid, in which case the offset number will be printed and that offset will be skipped over.
    """
    data = []
    skipped_offset = []
    for i in range(start, num_results, 20):        
        res = propublica_data(statement_url + f"&offset={i}")
        if res.get("results") == None:
            skipped_offset.append(i)
            continue
        res = res["results"]        
        if len(res) == 0:
            break
        if type_ == "statement":
            df = pd.DataFrame(res)
            df["date"] = df["date"].apply(pd.to_datetime)
        elif type_ == "bill":
            df = pd.DataFrame(res[0]["bills"])
            df[["introduced_date", "latest_major_action_date"]] = df[["introduced_date", "latest_major_action_date"]].apply(pd.to_datetime)
        data.append(df)
    print(skipped_offset)
    if len(data) > 1:
        return pd.concat(data)
    elif len(data) == 1:        
        return data[0]
    return pd.DataFrame()

def get_all_statements(url):
    """
    Given url without offset get all results for statment search based on query.
    Returns concatenated df.
    """
    num_results = propublica_data(url).get("num_results")
    if num_results == None:
        return pd.DataFrame()
    # can only get 5000 requests at once
    max_requests = 5000
    if num_results > max_requests:
        dfs = []
        for start in range(0, num_results, max_requests):            
            df = statements_paginated(url, start + max_requests, start)            
            dfs.append(df)
#             time.sleep(10)
        return pd.concat(dfs)
    else:
        df = statements_paginated(url, num_results)        
        return df

def graph_differences(df):
    
    # add column that specifies if in recession
    def day_in_recession(x):
        """
        Returns true if day in recession, false otherwise.
        """
        for rr in recession_range.values:
            if x in rr:
                return True
        return False
    df["in_recession"] = df["date"].apply(day_in_recession)
    
    # graph total statments for all sessions
    session_recession = df.groupby(["congress", "in_recession"]).count()["url"]
    session_recession = session_recession.to_frame().rename(columns={"url": "count"})
    sns.catplot(x="congress", y="count", hue="in_recession", data=session_recession.reset_index(), kind="bar")
    
    #graph statements per day for all sessions
    session_recession
    # gets number of unique days with statements per session and recession status
    dates_per_sr = df[["congress", "in_recession", "date"]].groupby(["congress", "in_recession"]).nunique().rename(columns={"date": "count"})
    # gives statements per day mentioning unemployment for days in and out of recessions
    statements_per_day = session_recession/dates_per_sr
    statements_per_day
    sns.catplot(x="congress", y="count", hue="in_recession", data=statements_per_day.reset_index(), kind="bar")

    # now drop sessions that don't have both recessions and not recessions
    recession_and_not = statements_per_day.reset_index().groupby("congress")["in_recession"].agg(len) > 1
    statements_per_day.reset_index()["congress"].isin(recession_and_not)
    both_rec = statements_per_day.loc[recession_and_not[recession_and_not].index]
    sns.catplot(x="congress", y="count", hue="in_recession", data=both_rec.reset_index(), kind="bar")
    
    return statements_per_day

# look at congressional sessions 115 and 116 -- from 2017 to 2021
def get_congress_members(congress_sessions):
    congress_members_dfs = []
    for con in congress_sessions:
        for ch in ["house", "senate"]:
            url = f"https://api.propublica.org/congress/v1/{con}/{ch}/members.json"
            df = pd.DataFrame(propublica_data(url)["results"][0]["members"])
            # add column with congressional session
            df["congress"] = con
            congress_members_dfs.append(df)
    congress_members = pd.concat(congress_members_dfs)
    # add new column to congress_members with name of form (last_name, first_name)
    congress_members["full_name"] = congress_members["last_name"] + ", " + congress_members["first_name"]
    return congress_members

def statements_by_name(full_name, sessions):
    """
    Given full name finds member id from congress_members df, then finds all statements in the given congressional sessions.
    Returns df with all statements.
    """
    # only get one row with Congressmember's full_name because many congressmembers serve multiple terms and thus will have multiple rows in df
    member_id = congress_members.drop_duplicates(subset="full_name", keep="first").set_index("full_name").loc[full_name, "id"]
#     print(member_id)
    dfs = []
    for s in sessions:
        url = f"https://api.propublica.org/congress/v1/members/{member_id}/statements/{s}.json?"
        df = get_all_statements(url)
        # adds name and congressional session to each row for ease of grouping
        if ~df.empty:
            df["name"] = full_name
            df["session"] = s
            dfs.append(df)        
    return pd.concat(dfs)

Write a function to graph congressional action (like statements and bills) given a df with said data and the names and campaign start/end dates of candidates.

In [11]:
def graph_congress_actions(df, campaign_dates):
    """
    Takes a df with congressional actions taken by Congress members with an index of (name, date)
    (with the Congress members as the keys of campaign_dates) and graphs it over time with shading based on campaign_dates.
    Returns the resulting figure.
    """
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(6, 2, figsize=(10, 14))
    for name, a in zip(campaign_dates.keys(), ax.flatten()):
        curr_df = df.loc[name, :, :].reset_index("name", drop=True)
        curr_df.plot(ax=a, xlabel="", ylabel="", color="royalblue", zorder=2)  
        cds = campaign_dates[name]
        a.set_title(name, fontname="Palatino Linotype")
        a.grid(zorder=0, alpha=0.5)
        a.tick_params(axis="y", color="gray", length=7)
        a.tick_params(axis="x", which="both", color="gray", length=4)
        a.axvspan(cds[0], cds[1], alpha=0.1, color="black")
#         a.set_facecolor(facecolor)
        remove_spines(a, sides=["top", "right", "bottom", "left"])
    fig.tight_layout()
    return fig

def bills_by_member(member_id, bill_type):
    """
    Gets all bills given member id and bill_type (introduced, updated, active, passed, enacted or vetoed)
    """
    url = f"https://api.propublica.org/congress/v1/members/{member_id}/bills/{bill_type}.json?" # DON'T FORGET '?' in urls!!
    num_results = propublica_data(url)["results"][0]["num_results"]
    return statements_paginated(url, num_results, type_="bill")

def bills_all_members(member_ids, bill_type):
    """
    Gets all bills for a list of congressmembers given their member ids.
    """
    dfs = []
    for m_id in member_ids:
        df = bills_by_member(m_id, bill_type)        
        dfs.append(df)
    return pd.concat(dfs)

def graph_vote_stats(vote_df, stat_name, member_names):
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(6, 2, figsize=(10, 14)) #, sharey=True)
    for name, a in zip(member_names, ax.flatten()):
        df = vote_df.loc[name, ["congress", stat_name]].reset_index("full_name", drop=True).set_index("congress")
        colors = ["royalblue" if x == 116 else "gainsboro" for x in df.index]
        # need to make df into series to cycle colors in plot
        (df[stat_name].plot(ax=a, kind="bar", title=name, legend=False, zorder=2,
              xlabel="", ylabel="", color=colors)
        )
        a.set_title(name, fontname="Palatino Linotype")
        a.grid(axis="y", zorder=0, alpha=0.5)
        a.tick_params(axis="y", color="gray", length=7)
        a.tick_params(axis="x", which="both", color="gray", length=4, labelrotation=0)
        remove_spines(a, sides=["top", "right", "bottom", "left"])
    fig.delaxes(ax.flatten()[-1])
    return fig

So, of the members who were in congress for the given sessions, it seems as if presidential candidates vote more against their party -- in fact, their percentage of votes against their party are nearly double the percentage of votes against party of non-presidential candidates. Compared with democrats who were not presidential candidates, the presidential candidates percentage of votes against their party was nearly 4 times as large. This poses another interesting question: do more independently minded (i.e., don't always go along with their party) candidates self-select for presidential runs? Perhaps. As seen above, they voted significantly (but not sure if it is statistically significant; need further analysis for that) less with their party in sessions 115-116, though in 113 and 114 they appear to be about average. Since 115 was the first two years of Trump's term, this could be seen as posturing -- or, these were the congresspeople with the most ideas independent of their party who believed they could better lead their party & somewhat change its direction.

Now, I'll turn to examining effectiveness to see if the presidential candidates were the ones with the most active bills or became the ones with the most active bills during their campaign period.

def cand_fec_data(cand_names):
    dfs = []
    for name in cand_names:
        cand_name = ("%20").join(name.split(", "))
        url = "https://api.open.fec.gov/v1/candidates/search/?sort=name&api_key=" + fec_api_key + "&sort_null_only=false&sort_hide_null=false&q=" + cand_name + "&page=1&per_page=20&sort_nulls_last=false"
        df = pd.DataFrame(fec_data(url)["results"])
        dfs.append(df)
    return pd.concat(dfs)

def fec_cand_info(cand_ids):
    """
    Get campaign funds info given FEC candidate id Series w/ candidate id and corresponding name.
    """
    dfs = []
    cand_id_list = list(cand_ids["candidate_id"])
    for cand_id in cand_id_list:
        url = "https://api.open.fec.gov/v1/candidate/" + cand_id + "/totals/?sort_hide_null=false&api_key=" + fec_api_key + "&page=1&sort_null_only=false&per_page=20&sort_nulls_last=false&sort=-cycle"
        df = pd.DataFrame(fec_data(url)["results"])
        dfs.append(df)
    dfs_concat = pd.concat(dfs).merge(cand_ids, on="candidate_id")
    # make cycle years into datetime
    dfs_concat["cycle"] = dfs_concat["cycle"].apply(pd.to_datetime, format="%Y")
    return dfs_concat

def remove_middle_initial(x):
    """
    Removes middle initial (either followed by a "." or not) and returns result.
    """
    return re.sub(r"\s[A-Z]{1,2}\.$|\s[A-Z]$", "", x).title()

def compare_items(pres_df, cong_df, columns, agg_func=sum):
    """
    Given an FEC campaign funds df of presidential fundraising and congressional fundraising for the same candidates,
    returns merged df with presidential and congressional fundraising compared on the given columns using the given aggregate function.
    """
    def group_df(df, agg_func):
        """
        Groups df by given aggregate function and removes middle initial from name in df.
        """
        new_df = df.groupby("name")[columns].apply(agg_func).reset_index()
        new_df["name"] = new_df["name"].apply(remove_middle_initial)
        return new_df  
    
    df1 = group_df(pres_df, sum)
    df2 = group_df(cong_df, agg_func)
    return df1.merge(df2, on="name", suffixes=[" presidential", " congressional"])

column = "individual_itemized_contributions"
ind_contributions_df = compare_items(cand_fec_money, cong_cand_fec_money, [column], sum) #np.mean #for avg--though bernie's is small, may need to break into House and Senate runs

def graph_fec_differences(fec_diff_df, column):
    """
    Takes a df formed with the compare_items function (with two columns, one for presidential and one for congressional)
    and returns a figure with two subplots, one with data from each column.
    """
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(12, 4), sharey=True)
    column_title = " ".join(column.title().split("_"))
    for i, cand_type in enumerate(["congressional", "presidential"]):
        a = ax[i]
        fec_diff_df.set_index("name")[column + " " + cand_type].plot(ax=a, kind="bar", xlabel="", 
                                                                     zorder=2, color="royalblue",)
        a.set_title("Total " + cand_type.title() + " "+ column_title, pad=20, fontname="Palatino Linotype", fontweight=400, fontsize=14)
        a.set_xticklabels(a.get_xticklabels(), rotation=320, ha="left")
        a.grid(axis="y", zorder=0, alpha=0.5)
    remove_spines(ax)
#     fig.tight_layout()
    return fig

def one_graph_fec_differences(fec_diff_df, column):
    """
    Takes a df formed with the compare_items function (with two columns, one for presidential and one for congressional)
    and returns a figure with one plot, with a bar representing data from each column.
    """
    fig, a = plt.subplots(figsize=(12, 4), sharey=True)
    column_title = " ".join(column.title().split("_"))
#     a = ax[i]
    fec_diff_df.set_index("name").plot(ax=a, kind="bar", xlabel="",

    a.grid(axis="y", zorder=0, alpha=0.5)
    remove_spines(a)

    return fig

def graph_fec_ratio(fec_diff_df, column):
    """
    Takes a df formed with the compare_items function (with two columns, one for presidential and one for congressional)
    and returns a figure with the ratio of presidential to congressional.
    """
    contributions_ratio = fec_diff_df[column + " presidential"].divide(fec_diff_df[column + " congressional"]).to_frame("presidential-to-congressional contributions").join(contributions_df[["name"]])
    column_title = " ".join(column.title().split("_"))
    fig, ax = plt.subplots()
    contributions_ratio.set_index("name").plot(ax=ax, kind="bar", legend=False, zorder=2, color="royalblue", xlabel="")
    ax.set_title("Ratio of Presidential to Total Congressional " + column_title, pad=20)
    ax.grid(axis="y", zorder=0)
    ax.set_xticklabels(ax.get_xticklabels(), rotation=320, ha="left")
    remove_spines(ax)
    fig.tight_layout()
    return fig
fig = graph_fec_ratio(ind_contributions_df, column)

def fec_compare_and_graph(pres_df, cong_df, column, agg_func=sum):
    """
    Given fec df corresponding with presidential fundraising data and congressional fundraising data creates two graphs;
    one shows presidential side-by-side with congressional (sum is default, could be mean, median, etc.) 
    data for provided column.
    Returns both figures.
    """
    column_df = compare_items(pres_df, cong_df, [column], agg_func)
    fig_1 = one_graph_fec_differences(column_df, column)
    fig_2 = graph_fec_ratio(column_df, column)
    return fig_1, fig_2

*Sanders example

So, in all of Bernie's presidential runs, he's raised significantly more than he's raised in all his Congressional runs -- almost 5 times as much. This graph is significant as it shows how much money candidates raised relative to their total congressional fundraising. A higher ratio means they outperformed their congressional fundraising by a lot; a lower ratio means they couldn't channel as much enthusiasm and boost themselves relative to their pre-campaign image.

Note: this ratio needs to be paired with total fundraising graphs (which are above). Perhaps if one is already raising so much money in a congressional campaign, this ratio could be low, as their could be little room to elevate their fundraising relative to its normal amount.

Note: DO NOT trust these numbers. This is preliminary analysis. Make sure I'm not double counting rows in df. GROUPBY election year, not cycle? or just say cycles 2018, 2020 for pres run?
